{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471652"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:50:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:50:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"381"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/381"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.66,0.05,0.08,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"381"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79041"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/381"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"381"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64393"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1865"},{"type":"tags","id":"9089"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"},{"type":"tags","id":"11176"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1157"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1346"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79041"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA newborn boy is assessed on the Maternity Ward with bilious vomiting since birth four hours ago. He has not passed meconium and is not tolerating feeds. He was diagnosed with Trisomy 21 on prenatal testing. He has no other medical history and takes no medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 160/min, blood pressure 65/40 mmHg, respiratory rate 60/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His abdomen is distended in the upper quadrants. Blood gas analysis shows pH 7.50, bicarbonate 28 mmol/L (22-26), chloride 90 mmol/L (98-106).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely finding on abdominal X-ray?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Target sign","Double bubble","Malposition of vessels","Coffee bean sign","Multiple air fluid levels"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant presents with classic features of duodenal atresia: early-onset bilious vomiting, upper abdominal distension, and hypochloraemic metabolic alkalosis. The association with Trisomy 21 further supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edouble bubble\u003C/strong\u003E sign is pathognomonic of duodenal atresia or stenosis. It appears on abdominal X-ray as two adjacent air-filled spaces in the upper abdomen, representing a dilated stomach and proximal duodenum. The obstruction prevents air from passing beyond this point.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etarget sign\u003C/strong\u003E (also called \u0027bull\u0027s eye\u0027 sign) is seen in intussusception, where one segment of bowel telescopes into another. This typically presents in infants 3-12 months of age with intermittent abdominal pain and bloody stools.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoffee bean sign\u003C/strong\u003E appears in cases of sigmoid volvulus, where the dilated bowel loop resembles a coffee bean. This is extremely rare in neonates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalposition of vessels\u003C/strong\u003E would be seen on angiography rather than plain radiography and is not relevant to the presenting symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple air fluid levels\u003C/strong\u003E are a non-specific finding seen in various causes of bowel obstruction or ileus. While these might be present, the double bubble sign is the characteristic finding in duodenal atresia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuodenal atresia requires urgent surgical correction. Initial management includes nasogastric decompression, fluid resuscitation, and correction of electrolyte abnormalities before definitive repair.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The double bubble sign on abdominal X-ray is pathognomonic of duodenal atresia or stenosis","Duodenal atresia commonly presents with early-onset bilious vomiting and upper abdominal distension","Duodenal atresia occurs in 20-30% of infants with Trisomy 21"],"references":["Bishop J, McCormick B, Johnson C, Miller J, Jelin E, Blakemore K et al. The Double Bubble Sign: Duodenal Atresia and Associated Genetic Etiologies. Fetal Diagnosis and Therapy. 2019;47(2):98-103. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31167209/","Stoll C, Dott B, Alembik Y, Roth M. Associated congenital anomalies among cases with Down syndrome. European Journal of Medical Genetics. 2015;58(12):674-680. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26578241/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64393"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"381"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64393"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T13:46:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T13:46:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"381"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79041"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"